In Linux, every file has a specific set of permissions. If you lack the necessary permission, you cannot run a script.

5. chmod (Change Mode)
In simple terms: Granting permission to run (execute) a file. When you download a tool from GitHub, it won't run until you make it executable.

Practical Example: Making a Python script named `exploit.py` executable:
Bash
chmod +x exploit.py
Now, you can run it by typing `./exploit.py`.

6. sudo (Superuser Do)
In simple terms: "Execute this command with the privileges of the system administrator (Root)."

Practical Example: Updating Kali Linux (the system will not grant permission without `sudo`):
Bash
sudo apt update
